column168: DOCK MAN WAS UNLOADING TRAILER WHEN HE DISCOVERED FOUR CARTONS WHICH HAD ABSORBED LIQUID ON THE BOTTOM.  FREIGHT WAS TRANSFERRED TO OS&D WHERE INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TWO TOPS ON TWO OF THE GLASS JUGS WERE LOOSE. THE CARTONS APPEAR TO HAVE SOAKED UP THE LIQUID PRIOR TO PICK UP BY CARRIER. column168: THE DELIVERY TRUCK WAS POSITIONED NEAR THE FILLS AT THE SERVICE STATION LOCATION PREPARING TO UNLOAD.  AS THE DRIVER OPENED THE VALVE TO COMMENCE DISCHARGING A WELDED ALUMINUM CAP ON THE LEFT END OF THE MANIFOLD RUPTURED.  THE TEAR WAS ALONG THE WELD BETWEEN THE CAP AND THE MANIFOLD ITSELF.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE VALVE AND CUT OFF THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  THE FINAL RESULT WAS APPROXIMATELY 5-10 GALONS OF GASOLINE ON THE PAVEMENT.  THE PUDDLE WAS DILUTED WITH WATER AND RAPIDLY EVAPORATED. THE D.E.P. WAS NOTIFIED AND WERE PRESENT AT THE SCENE.  THEIR ESTIMATE OF THE AMOUNT SPILLED WAS CLOSER TO 5 GALLONS.  THE TRUCK REMAINED LOADED AND RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL WHERE THE FAILED PIECE WAS REMOVED AND A NEW ONE FABRICATED.  THE FAILED PART IS BEING TAKEN TO FRUEHAUF FOR ANALYSIS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN A SINGLE VEHICLE ACCIDENT WHILE DRIVING ON A GRAVEL ROAD.  HE PROCEEDED AROUND A BEND IN THE ROAD.  AROUND THE BEND THE ROAD NARROWED.  THE VEHICLE'S FRONT WHEEL ON PASSENGER SIDE LEFT MAIN ROAD AND WENT ONTO SOFT SHOULDER WHICH COULD NOT SUPPORT THE WEIGHT OF THE VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED 3 TIMES AND CAME TO REST ON ITS TOP IN DEAD POINT CREEK.  ALL 2150 GALLONS OF OIL SPILLED INTO THE CREEK.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. AND SHERIFF DEPT. WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED.  THE OREGON DEQ AND U.S. COAST GUARD WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE PRODUCT FLOWED DOWNSTREAM AND WAS CONTAINED AT COPPER DAM.  RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL HAS BEEN CONTRACTED TO CLEAN UP THE CONTAMINATED AREA.
AAA COOPER TRANSPORTATION CENSUS REPORT NUMBER: 092261 THIS DEGREASER WAS USED ON THE DOCK ITSELF TO REMOVE DIRT AND OIL STAINS.

column168: WHEN OPENING ULD#2810 WE NOTICED A CARDBOARD BOX LEAKING AND GIVING OFF AN ODOR,  THE SUPERVISOR SECURED THE BOX AND REMOVED IT, MOVING IT OUTSIDE INTO THE OPEN AIR FOR INVESTIGATION.  THE OPERATIONS MGR, DENNIS MARTIN, IDENTIFIED INDIVIDUAL CONTAINERS AS HAVING WARNING LABELS OF A POTENTIAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  UPON NOTIFICATION OF OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPT. IN DAYTON, OH. WE THEN REQUESTED AN MSDS FROM THE SHIPPER IN ORDER THAT THE PRODUCT AS TRICHLOROETHYLENE.  THE PACKAGE ITSELF HAD NO INDICATION OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ONLY WARNINGS OF DANGER IF INHALED OR OVEREXPOSED. THERE WAS NO INNER PACKAGING WHATSOEVER AS THE 6 ONE GALLON METAL CONTAINERS WERE ALL PACKED IN THE BOX.  THE OPPORTUNITY FOR PUNCTURE OR SPILL WAS EVIDENT BY LACK OF ANY APPROPRIATE OR PROTECTIVE PACKAGING.

column168: A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED FROM THE REAR OF OUR TRAILER AT THE TOLL PLAZA ON I-94 IN WISCONSIN. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THE SERVICES OF REIDEL ENVIRONMETAL WAS SECURED TO PERFORM CLEAN-UP SERVICES.  A PORTABLE TANK OF COMBUSTIABLE LIQUID AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  A FAULTY GASKET AT THE TOP OF THE TANK WAS WHERE THE LEAKING ORIGINATED. column168: THIS UNIT WAS LOADED BY TH TERMINAL PRELOADER AND THEN PLACED ON TREMINAL YARD.  THE DRIVER DEPARTED PORT ALLEN, LA AND WHEN HE WAS ON I-20 WEST OF SHREVEPORT, LA.  A MAN IN A PICK UP TRUCK INDICATED TO OUR DRIVER THAT SOMETHING WAS WRONG WITH THE TRAILER.  THEN TWO CARS PASSED AND INDICATED TO OUR DRIVER THAT SOMETHING WAS WRONG. AS SOON AS THE DRIVER COULD STOP HE PULLED OVER TO CHECK THE TRAILER. ON TOP HE SAW STYRENE IN THE ROLL OVER PROTECTOR.  CHECKING THE DOME HE FOUND FOUR OF THE NUTS ON THE DOME COVER LOOSE AND PRODUCT LEAKING OUT.  HE PULLED THE NUTS TIGHT AND DROVE A SHORT DISTANCE TO A TRUCK STOP.  HE HAD BLUE BEACON TRUCK WASH WASH THE TRAILER.  THEN HE MOVED THE TRAILER BACK AND FORTH TO SEE IF THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.  IT HAD, SO HE DROVE A SHORT DISTANCE AND CHECKED IT FOR LEAKS AGAIN.  THE TRAILER LEAKED AGAIN IN DENNISON, TX.. THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE DRIVER WENT ON TO UNLOAD, WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE PRELOADED DID NOT CHECK THE DOME AFTER LOADING, BECAUSE THE PLANT WILL NOT ALLOW A DRIVER ON THE TRAILER.  NONE OF THE VEHICLES WHICH SIGNALED OUR DRIVER STOPPED, SO WE DON'T KNOW IF WE GOT STYRENE ON THEM OR NOT.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELLING NORTHBOUND ON I83.  IT WAS RAINING AND TRAFFIC HAD SLOWED TO A STOP FOR AN ACCIDENT ON THE ROADWAY AHEAD.  THE LEFFLER DRIVER APPLIED HIS BRAKES AND THE TANKWAGON SLID TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY.  WHEN THE TIRES HIT THE GRAVEL ON THE SHOULDER THE UNIT ROLLED COMPLETELY OVER AND LANDED ON ITS WHEELS.  THE FRONT COMPARTMENT WAS LOADED FULL AND RUPTURED AT THE BOTTOM.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT WITH THE PRODUCT GOING DOWN THE STORM SEWER INTO A CREEK.  THE HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND STOPPED MOST OF THE PRODUCT FROM GOING TOO FAR, USING BOOMS. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY LEFFLER PERSONNEL; WASTE WAS TAKEN TO POLLUTION CONTROL, DILLSBURG, PA.  ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INFORMED TO DRAW DOWN THEIR COMPARTMENTS MORE EVENLY TO PREVENT TOO MUCH WEIGHT BEING TOO FAR FORWARD ON THE LOAD OR TOO FAR BACK.  THE LEFFLER DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND CHECKED FOR INJURIES.  NO INJURIES WERE NOTED; ONLY SHAKEN UP.

column168: THE CARGO TANK WAS PARKED IN A COMPANY PARKING LOT.  IT WAS HOLDING APPROXIMATELY 19 BARRELS (798 GALLONS) OF INHIBITED HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION.  AN EMPLOYEE NOTICED THE TANK WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE LADING WAS TRANSFERED INTO AN EMPTY CARGO TANK.  AN ESTIMATED 2 BARRELS (84 GALLONS) OF MATERIAL SPILLED ON TO THE GROUND.  THE SPILL AREA WAS COVERED WITH SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  THE SANTA DE SPRINGS FIRE DEPARTMENT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED AND THEY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  INTERNATIONAL TECHNOLOGIES (IT) CORP. OF WILMINGTON, CALIF WAS HIRED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  AN EXAMINATION OF THE CARGO TANK REVEALED A 1/4 INCH HOLE CAUSED BY CORROSION ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK NEAR THE REAR.  THE TANK WAS EMPTIED, CLEANED AND INSPECTED BY THE STATION MANAGER.  HIS DECISION WAS TO DECLARE THE TANK INSERVICEABLE AND SENT IT TO THE COMPANY SALVAGE IN ODESSA, TEXAS.

WHILE LOADING PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK, DRIVER NOTICED ONE OF THE PRODUCT TRANSFER HOSES HAD DEVELOPED A BUBBLE IN THE OUTER LAYER OF HOSE MATERIAL.  DRIVER INITIATED ACTON, BUT WAS UNABLE TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT BEFORE THE HOSE RUPTURED.  APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY PLANT PERSONNEL THROUGH USE OF THE PLANTS HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL SYSTEM.  HOSE FAILURE WAS CAUSED BY A CRACK THAT WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE HOSE.  THIS ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SLOWLY WORK ITS WAY THROUGH THE VARIOUS LAYERS OF MATERIAL UNTIL THE HOSE FINALLY FAILED.  ALTHOUGH THE HOSE SHOWED NO OUTWARD APPEARANCE OF ANY DAMAGE, THE CRACK IS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY THE HOSE BEING OF ANY DAMAGE, THE TIME CRACK IS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY THE HOSE BEING "KINKED" AT SOME TIME PREVIOUS TO THE INCIDENT.  HOSE HAS BEEN DISCARDED.

column168: TWO (2) DRIVERS WERE PUMPING APPROXIMATELY 3600 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL OUT OF A 4000 GALLON UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK INTO A CARGO TANK.  THE CARGO TANK WAS SPLIT INTO FIVE COMPARTMENTS OF VARIOUS SIZES.  APPROXIMATELY 2850 GALLONS WAS PUMPED INTO A 2900 GALLON COMPARTMENT (LEVEL OF PRODUCT WAS BETWEEN 2900 GALLON AND THE 2800 GALLON MARKERS IN THE COMPARTMENT) AND THEN THE DRIVERS SWITCHED TO A 100 GALLON COMPARTMENT TO COMPLETE THE PUMP OUT (APPROXIMATELY 800 GALLONS REMAINED IN THE UNDERGROUND TANK). WHEN THE PUMP BEGAN SUCKING AIR, ONE DRIVER WENT INSIDE THE TRUCK TO SHUT DOWN THE PUMP WHILE THE OTHER WENT TO SHUT OFF THE HAND VALVE OF THE TANKER.  AT THIS TIME, THE DRIVER OUT OF THE TANKER HEARD PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE REAR OF THE TANKER, AND BOTH RAN IMMEDIATELY WITH BUCKETS AND ABSORBENT PADS TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM ENTERING A NEAR-BY STORM DRAIN.  ONCE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED, AS WELL AS THE UNITED STATES COAST GUARD.  OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE VEHICLE ALSO RESPONDED AND ALONG WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CLEANED-UP THE APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE US COAST GUARD OFFICIAL FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT ENTERING THE STORM DRAIN AND THEREFORE FELT THAT PUTTING AND ABSORBENT BOOM IN THE STORM DRAIN WAS UNNECESSARY. WHILE UNLOADING A SKID INTO TRAILER, THE EMPLOYEE INVOLVED NOTICED A CRUSHED BOX.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTING HE FOUND THAT THIS CONTAINED POISONOUS "B" LTD QTY.  HE THEN SWEPT CARTON OUT ONTO DOCK AREA - REPORTED THIS TO ME AND WENT TO WASHUP.  THE CARTON APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN RAMMED WITH ANOTHER PALLET AND WAS TOTALLY CRUSHED.  THE 2 BOTTLES INSIDE WERE DAMAGED, 1 TOTALLY CRUSHED THE OTHER HAD THE TOP CRACKED.  FRANK ELMER HAD CLEANED UP THE CONTENTS AND PUT INTO A REPACK DRUM TO BE DISPOSED OF BY RIEDEL, OUR HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL COMPANY.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR UNLOADING AT DESTINATION.  HE CONNECTED THE PRODUCT HOSE AND STARTED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL.  DURING THE TRANSFER PROCESS THE STAINLESS STEEL HOSE SPRUNG A LEAK.  OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN IMMEDIATELY AND ASSISTED IN THE CLEAN UP.  HE NOTIFIED HIS TERMINAL AND A REPLACEMENT HOSE WAS DISPATCHED FOR HIS USE.  HE CHANGED HOSES AND COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY WITHOUT FURRTHER DIFFICULTY.

SWITCHING CREW DETECTED ODOR OF LADING AROUND THE TANK CAR.  THE RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.  THE SITUATION WAS DISCUSSED WITH A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER.  AN INPECTION OF THE TANK CAR REVEALED NO VISIBLE LEAKS, EXCEPT AT THE BASE OF THE GAUGING DEVICE; HOWEVER, THIS COULD NOT BE CONFIRMED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR COULD BE SAFELY FORWARDED TO DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING AND AN IN-DEPTH INSPECTION OF THE GAUGING DEVICE AND GASKET.
A LEAKING DRUM WAS DISCOVERED UPON ARRIVAL AT DESTINATION.  THE DRUM HAD RUSTED OUT AT THE SEAM.  THE DRUM WAS PUT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  OIL DRY WAS PLACED ON SPILLED MATERIAL IN TRAILER.

THE THREE INCH RETAINING CAP ON THE PUMP CROSSOVER DISCHARGE LINE RUPTURED RESULTING IN A 15 TO 20 GALLON SPILL.  AFTER PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY CUSTOMER, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE INLET VALVE ON THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK HAD NOT BEEN OPENED BY CUSTOMER, RESULTING IN PRESSURE BUILD-UP IN PUMP.  IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT THE BY-PASS ON THE UNLOADING PUMP WAS INOPERATIVE.  PUMP WAS NEW AND HAD NEVER BEEN USED BEFORE.

DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS THE "CAM LOCK" FITTING CONNECTING THE UNLOADING HOSE TO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK VIBRATED LOOSE AND DISCONNECTED, RESULTING IN AN APPROXIMATE 50 GALLON SPILL.  PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY CUSTOMER.

column168: CUSTOMER TANK IS LOCATED INSIDE THEIR BUILDING IN A CONTAINMENT DIKE.  OUR DRIVER WAS OUTSIDE WITH HIS VEHICLE WHILE UNLOADING.  CUSTOMER WAS WATCHING HIS TANK. HE WAS NOT AWARE THAT THE STORAGE TANK HAD OVERFILLED. NOTE:  ALL SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY DESOTO INC., CUSTOMER.

column168: DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CARGO TANK WHILE STOPPED FOR FUEL.  UNIT WAS PULLED TO THE REAR OF THE TRUCKSTOP PARKING LOT AND A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE LEAK TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. ANOTHER UNIT WAS BROUGHT OT THE SITE AND THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. THE ONE PINT OF PRODUCT THAT WAS CONTAINED IN THE BUCKET WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE CARGO TANK AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH PROPER CLEANING OF THE TANK AT A COMPANY WASH FACILITY. TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO A COMMERCIAL REPAIR FACILITY WHERE THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN COMING FROM A CRACKED WELD IN THE TANK SUMP.  REPAIRS HAVE BEEN MADE.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT DESTINATION AND WAS CLEARED FOR UNLOADING.  WHEN HE REMOVED THE CAP ON THE OUTLET LINE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE LINE UNTIL HE WAS ABLE TO CONNECT THE UNLOADING HOSE.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CUSTOMER.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE VALVE SEAT MATERIAL AND GASKET MATERIAL THAT THE TERMINAL USED WAS NOT COMPATIBLE WITH THE PRODUCT CAUSING THE PROBLEM.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT DESTINATION.  HE PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE WHICH WAS INSIDE THE PLANT AND NOT WITHIN VIEW OF OUR DRIVER.  AS OUR TRAILER WET EMPTY THE CUSTOMER'S TANK OVERFLOWED,  THE CUSTOMER HAD INCORRECTLY GAUGED THE CAPACITY OF THEIR STORAGE TANK.  THEY TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN UP.

IT WAS THEN COLLECTED AND STORED IN RECOVERY DRUM.  FOUR SEASONS IND SERVICES OF 207 ROBBINS ST, GREENSBORO, NC REMOVED ALL MATERIAL AND PUT IN RECOVERY DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.

A TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY THE DRIVER ENROUTE TO DETROIT, MI NEAR HUNTINGTON, IN.  THE INDIANA STATE POLICE AND THE HUNTINGTON, IN CIVIL DEFENSE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED AND THE TRAILER WAS FORWARDED TO DETROIT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: DISCOVERED AN ALKALINE LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF A TRAILER ALONG I-81.  THE VIRGINIA STATE POLICE NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY.  THE TRAILER CONTAINED A FLAMMABLE LIQUID WITH A SECONDARY POISON INHALATION HAZARD, WHICH CAUSED A DRASTIC OVERREACTION BY ALL REGULATORY PERSONNEL.  THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID/POISON INHALATION WAS NOT DAMAGED OR LEAKING IN ANY MANNER.  THE CORROSIVE WAS SEEPING FROM A LOOSE FITTING LID WITH MINIMAL SPILLAGE.  THE DRIVER HAD TOUCHED THE REAR TRAILER DOOR HANDLE AND GOT A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE CORROSIVE ON HIS HANDS.  THE INTERSTATE PLUS NUMEROUS OTHER BUSINESSES ALONG THE INTERSTATE WERE EVACUATED FOR SEVERAL HOURS UNTIL THE SPECIFIC CAUSE AND THE QUANTITY WAS DISCOVERED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED PER 171.15.

A TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL AT THE RELAY TERMINAL.  A CERTIFIED EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY RESPONDED TO THE SCEEN AND RECOOPERED THE SPILLAGE TO INCLUDE REMOVAL/DISPOSAL OF A PORTION OF THE TRAILER FLOORING.

WHILE ON THE TRAILER ONE 350 GALLON TOTE TANK WAS FOUND LEAKING.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND SENT OUT PEOPLE TO HANDLE THE PROPER CLEANUP OF THE SPILLAGE AND THE PROPER HANDLING OF THE DAMAGED TOTE TANK.

WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER ONE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS FOUND DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  THE DRUM WAS RECOOPERED AND PLACED INTO A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.  THE SPILLAGE WAS ABSORBED WITH FLOOR DRY AND ALSO PLACED IN THE SAME RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.  ALL RESIDUE WAS CLEANSED FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.

WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER ONE 55 GALLON METAL DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING. THE DRUM WAS RECOOPERED AND PLACED IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR EXCHANGE. THE SPILLAGE WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP.

WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER ONE 35 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS FOUND LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM SEAM.  THE DRUM WAS RECOOPERED AND PLACED INTO A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR EXCHANGE.  THE SPILLAGE WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:50AM, 10-03-90, A TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT CO. DRIVER OBSERVED LIQUID MATERIAL DRIPPING FROM THE LEFT FRONT CORNER OF HIS TRAILER WHILE IN THE EASTBOUND REST AREA AT THE 140 MILE MARKER ON I-40. JUST WEST OF NORTH LITTLE ROCK, AR.  THE TRUCK WAS LADEN WITH 4,200 GALLONS OF WASTE, SUBSTITUTED NITROPHENOL PESTICIDE, LIQUID, N.O.S., FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN2780 (DINOSEB), PACKAGED IN 5 GALLON STEEL CONTAINERS. SPILTECH, INC., LITTLE ROCK, AR, WAS CALLED BY TRI-STATE TO CONTAIN AND STOP THE LEAK.  IT WAS DISCOVERED BY SPILTECH PEOPLE THAT THE PLASTIC WRAPPING HAD FAILED ON A SINGLE PALLET IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER LOADED WITH 42 CONTAINERS STACKED 3 HIGH.  THIS ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 10 CONTAINERS TO FALL TO THE SIDE.  ONE CONTAINER FAILED ALLOWING ABOUT 3 GALLONS TO RELEASE.  THE CONTAINER FAILURE WAS DUE TO A PIN HOLE NEAR THE LIFT HANDLE ON THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  THE ARKANSAS OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, ARKANSAS DEPARTMENT OF POLLUTION CONTROL AND ECOLOGY, AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE ALL NOTIFIED (NRC REPORT NO. 42484).  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO A NORTH LITTLE ROCK HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM AFTER COMING INTO CONTACT WITH THE DINOSEB.  HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  FOLLOWING INSTRUCTIONS IN THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK, AN EVACUATION OF A 1/2 MILE RADIUS WAS ORDERED BY THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE.  THIS INCLUDED APPROXIMATELY 100 HOMES AND AN UNKNOWN NUMBER OF PROPLE.  EVACUATED PERSONS WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMED BY 7:00AM 10-04-90.  CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED ON 10-05-90 AND TRUCK PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SEPCIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS C.L. HILL WAS CONTACTED BY MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS ROB SCHOULTZ ADVISING SUBJECT TANK CAR WAS IN NORTH LITTLE ROCK INBOUND YARD RELEASING VAPORS. MR. HILL'S INSPECTION DETERMINED VAPORS RELEASING BETWEEN MANWAY NOZZLE AND MANWAY COVER PLATE, PRESSURE READING SHOWED FIVE POOUNDS OF PRESSURE ON CAR.  CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED AREA WHERE 3/5" AIR IMPACT WRENCH WAS USED TO TIGHTEN DOWN MANWAY COVER PLATE TO NOZZLE WHICH WAS SECURED AT 0800 HOURS.  MR HILL CONTACTED SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE GERALD MARTIN WHO WAS INFORMED OF EXCEPTION NOTED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.

AT 0010 HOURS ON 10-22-90, UPRR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS A.J. GARDNER WAS NOTIFIED BY UPRR WEST YARDMASTER JOHN ROWLANDS ADVISING THAT ONE OF THREE TANK CARS CONTAINING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAS LEAKING. INSPECTION OF TANKS CARS IN QUESTION DEVELOPED THAT TANK CAR TGPX 33609 WAS LEAKING LIQUIED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AT A SLOW RATE FROM THE A-END LIQUID LINE VALVE FLANGE AND/OR THE VALVE STEM.  MR GARDNER ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN FLANGE BOLTS AND TIGHTLY SECURE THE VALVE HANDLE WITH NO SUCCESS.  AT 0215 HOURS. MR. GARDNER CONTACTED CHEMTREEC TO OBTAIN ASSISTANCE FROM THE SHIPPER.  CHEMTREC ESTABLISHED A CONFERENCE CALL WITH FARMLAND INDUSTRIES REPRESENTATIVE JOHN GOBLE OF KANSAS CITY, MO AT O230 HOURS.  MR. GOBLE ADVISED THAT HE WOULD ASSUME RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE LEAKING TANK AND WOULD DISPATCH TRUCKS TO THE SCENE AROUND 0800 HOURS TO OFF-LOAD TANK CAR TGPX 33609. AT 0300 HOURS, MR GARDNER CONTACTEC UPRR'S MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE IN KANSAS CITY TO GIVE AN UPDATE ON THE LEAKING CAR AND HE SUGGESTED THAT SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERILS D.A. LOW BE CONTACTED TO ASSIST WITH THE IMPENDING TRANSFER. WHEN MR.  LOW ARRIVED ON SCENE IT WAS DECIDED TO MAKE ANOTHER ATTEMPT TO REPAIR THE LEAKING CAR.  INSPECTION BY MR.  LOW DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKAGE WAS FROM THE VALVE STEM PACKING GLAND.  AT 0945 HOURS, AFTER DISMANTLING THE LIQUID VALVE STEM, NEW PACKING WAS APPLIED STOPPING LEAK. CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

WHILE INSPECTING TANK CARS, CHEYENNE YARDS, SWITCH CREW NOTIFIED UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS A.D. LOW OF TANK CAR LEAKING, SOUTH 7 TRACK.  INSPECTION BY MR. LOW DETERMINED THAT THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS LOOSE.  HE CLEANED, TAPED AND SECURED VALVE PROPERLY WHICH MITIGATED LEAK.  MR. LOW CONTACTED MR. KERRY HADDOCK, MATERIAL MANAGER, NU-WEST INDUSTRIES, AND ADVISED HIM OF THIS INCIDENT.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS D.D. MCCARTNEY WAS ADVISED BY CAR DEPARTMENT INSPECTORS THAT CAR GATX 17227, PHOSPHORIC ACID, ENTRAINED IN THE BORAH LOCAL, ON RECEIVING YARD TRACK NO. 7 WAS LEAKING OUT THE BOTTOM.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING OUT THE BOTTOM NEAR THE MIDDLE, AT THE B-END AROUND BODY BOLSTER AND SUBSEQUENTLY STARTED LEAKING AROUND BODY BOLSTER ON A-END OF CAR.  IT WAS EVIDENT THAT THE INSIDE RUBBER LINING HAD FAILED AND IT WAS NECESSARY TO OFF-LOAD THE CAR'S CONTENTS.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND THEIR RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED.  TRANSFER OPERATIONS BEGAN AT 12:00M NOON AND WHERE COMPLETED AT 1500 HOURS.  THE PRODUCT THAT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE AREA WAS CLEANED.  THE CARS WERE CARDED BACK TO THE J. R. SIMPLOT PLANT.

HOUSTON DRIVER/SALESMAN VIC BARTRAN WAS UNLOADING THIS SHIPMENT OF 10 DRUMS WITH BARREL DOLLY.  ONE DRUM WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED TO THE BARREL DOLLY AND SLID OFF OF THE DOLLY ONTO ITS SIDE.  THE BOTTOM PRONG OF THE BARREL DOLLY PUNCTURED A SMALL HOLE IN THE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF THE MATERIAL SPILLED OUT ONTO THE DOCK.

OUR CARGO TANK WAS TRANSPORTING PETROLEUM NAPHTHA COMBUSTIBEL LIQUID IN COMPARTMENT ONE.  APPROXIMATLEY TWO TO THREE GALLONS OF MINERAL SPIRITS CAME OUT OF THE DOME COVER AS THIS CARGO TANK PULLED IN TO TOLL PLAZA #41 ON 1294.  THE TOLL ROAD MAINTENANCE CREW CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MINERAL SPIRITS WITH SAND AND PLACED THAT SAND INTO A DRUM.  THE DRUM WHICH CONTAINED ABOUT 20 GALLONS OF SAND, WAS TRANSPORTED THE NEXT DAY TO MILWAUKEE SOLVENTS & CHEMICAL CORPORATION'S LICENSED FACILITY AT 14765 WEST BOBOLINK AVENUE IN MENONOMEE FALLS, WI 53051.  THERE WAS NO ACCIDENT, INJURY OR PROPERTY DAMAGE ASSOCITED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  THE ILLINOIS STATE PATROL OFFICERS AT THE SCENE, ASSISTED WITH DRIVER IN MAKING THE IMMEDIATE REPORTS REQUIRED.  THEY ALSO ASSISTED OUR DRIVER IN THE IMMEDIATE INVESTIGATION OF THIS INCIDENT.  THE FINDING WAS THAT TWO OF THE FOUR CAMLOCK CLOSURES WERE NOT SECURE ON THE DOME COVER.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED ON 1-800-782-7860 AND WAS ASSIGNED REPORT #90395.  WITH THE DOME COVERS SECURED AND THE MINERAL SPIRITS CLEANED UP THE DRIVER WAS ISSUED COMPLIANCE CHECK FORM 1LC57451 AND PROCEEDED WITH HIS DELIVERY.  NO PHOTOS WERE TAKEN.  AS ADDITIONAL FOLLOW-UP, OUR COMPANY CONTACTED THE CARGO TANK MANAUFACTURER POLAR INC. AND WAS INFORMED BY THEIR ENGINEERING DEPARTMENT THAT THIS CAMLOACK CLOSURE HAS BEEN USDED FOR MANY YEARS AND IS STILL IN USE ON NEW TANKESR.  VERY FEW PROBLEMS HAVE BEEN REPORTED TO THEM.  TO INSURE THAT AN INCIDENT OF THIS TYPE WILL NOT BE REPEATED WE HAVE ORDRED THE PARTS TO CONVERT THE CAMLOCK CLOSURES ON THIS COMPARTMETN TO SCREW DOEN CLOSURES TO FURTHER INSURE THAT AN INCIDENT OF THIS TYPE WILL NOT BE REPEATED.  WE ARE FILING THIS REPORT BECAUSE THE ILLINOIS OFFICER CIRCLES 5800.1 ON THE COMPLIANCE CHECK FORM.  THIS INCIDENT MAY NOT HAVE REQUIRED THE SUBMISSION OF THIS FEDERAL FORM; IF THAT IS THE CASE, WE ARE SUBMITTING IT FOR THE RECORD.  PLEASE CONTACT US IF THERE IS ANY ADDITIONAL FOLLOW UP AS WE SHOULD BE DOING IN REGARD TO THIS INCIDENT.

UPRR DISTRICT SPECIAL AGENT J.C. SWINEHART NOTIFIED SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS D.W. ALM OF A LEAKING TRAILER AT THE UPRR RENO, NEVADA INTERMODAL TRANSFER FACILITY.  MR. ALM RESPONDED AND FOUND TRAILER SFVZ 631580 WITH A WHITE SUBSTANCE ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER AT THE FRONT. THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS WASHED AND THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED AT 1600 HOURS.  SHIPPING PAPERS WERE CORRECT.

column168: PROBLEMS DEVELOPED ON TANK CAR GATX 41086 WHILE IT WAS BEING SWITCHED IN THE YARD AT ODGEN, UTAH.  SWITCH CREW REPORTED LEAK FROM THE CENTER DOME. INSPECTION OF CAR DETERMINED THE CENTER MANWAY COVER PLATE WAS MISSING. CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH THREE MANWAY OPENINGS.  THE COVER PLATE AND ONE BOLT WERE LOCATED AND REATTACHED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 0720 HOURS AND THEY NOTIFIED MR. JOHN COCHRAINE OF J.R. SIMPLOT.  THE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE UPFE TRACK WHERE A SPILL PAD AND CATCH BASIN WERE AVAILBALE.  THE CAR WAS WASHED AND CLEANED AND TWO SPILL AREAS IN THE YARD WERE NEUTRALIZED WITH 200 LBS. OF SODIUM BICARBONATE.  ADDITIONALLY, CARS SOU 19426, A BOX CAR, AND CAR UP21711, A BULK HEAD FLAT, WERE WASHED AS THEY WERE COVERED WITH THE COMMUNITY.  THE GASKET WAS CHECKED AND APPEARED TO BE SERVICEABLE, THE MANWAY COVER PLATE WAS POSITIONED AND SECURED INTO PLACE.  THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO SEE IF IT WOULD LEAK, REINSPECTED, AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  IT WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: TANK CAR GATX 41086 ARRIVED YERMO, CALIFORNIA IN TRAIN HKYR-13 AT 0530 HOURS.  CAR DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEES, WHILE INSPECTING THE TRAIN, OBSERVED AN EXCESSIVE AMOUNT OF MOISTURE ON THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE TANK CAR.  CAR WAS BAD ORDERED AND SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK.  INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE CENTER MANWAY COVER PLATE (ROUNDED) WAS LAYING FULLY OPEN WITH THREE (3) OF THE FOUR (4) SECURING BOLTS MISSING.  THE HINGE AND HINGE ROD FOR THE COVER PLATE WERE BENT AND WOULD ONLY ALLOW THE COVER PLATE TO CLOSE WITHIN SIX (6) INCHES OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  THE SHIPPER, SIMPLOT, CONTACTED THE GATX REPAIR FACILITY IN COLTON, CALIFORNIA TO MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE TANK CAR.S  THE MANWAY GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE COVER PLATE RE-SECURED.  EVEN THOUGH THE COVER PLATE WAS DISTORTED, WAS ABLE TO SECURE IT SUFFICIENTLY TO HOLD THE LADING.  THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ASSURE ADEQUATE CONTAINMENT, THEN SWITCHED TO THE DIESEL TRACK WHERE THE RESIDUE WAS WASHED FROM THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE CAR.  WILL NOTIFY SIMPLOT TO HAVE THE CAR BAD ORDERED AFTER BEING UNLOADED AND THEN ORDER REPLACEMNT PARTS TO EFFECT PROPER REPAIRS ONCE THE CAR IS SENT TO REPAIR FACILITY.  CHEMTREC ADVISED AT 1940 HOURS.

ATTACHED YOU WILL FIND A STATEMENT FROM THE DRIVER'S INVOLVED WHICH EXPLAINS THE INCIDENT. THIS WAS A FREAK INCIDETN AND WE WERE NEVER ABLE TO PINPOINT HUMAN OR MECHANICAL ERROR. ALL OF THE EQUIPMENT WAS GONE OVER AND NO MALFUNCTIONS WERE DETECTED. HE HAVE SINCE DECIDED TO DISCONTINUE TRANSFERRING LOADS FROM ONE TANKER TO ANOTHER. AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 A.M., WE WERE TRANSFERING A BULK LOAD OF HEXANE WITH VINYL ACETATE FROM VAC TRAILER TO TANKER USING VAC PUMP FOR UNLOADING. GETTING CLOSE TO END OF THE TRANSFER, I SHUT OFF VAC PUMP. SHORTLY THEREAFTER, AIR HIT THE LOADED TANKER AND BLEW THE CHEMICAL OUT OF THE DOME LID. WE WERE UNABLE TO REACH THE SHUT OFF VALVES DUE TO THE CHEMICAL SPILLAGE. THE CHEMICAL CONTINUED TO LEAK UNTIL ALL AIR PRESSURE WAS GONE. I CONTACTED CHEMICAL RECLAMATION SERVICE IMMEDIATELY AND THEY NOTIFIED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES. CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP STARTED IMMEDIATELY. JOHN APPLEGATE AND MYSELF SOUGHT MEDICAL ATTENTION AND WERE CHECKED AND RELEASED WITH NO INJURY.

NON-REVENUE PASSENGER CHARLES KIRKLAND OFFERED A CARDBOARD BOX LABELED "CLOTHING" AT MIDWAY AIRLINES OMAHA STATION FOR TRANSPORT TO PHOENIX AS PART OF HIS BELONGINGS.  PASSENGER KIRKLAND DID NOT DECLARE THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX TO OUR TICKET AGENT EVEN THOUGH THE FAA REQUIRED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SIGN WAS PROMINENTLY DISPLAYED. BOX WAS ACCEPTED FOR SHIPMENT AS CHECKED BAGGAGE SINCE THE LABEL READ CLOTHING.  UPON ARRIVAL/UNLOADING AT PHOENIX, THE BOX WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  WHILE HANDLING THE BOX, THE CONTAINER TORE OPEN AND AN AUTOMOBILE BATTERY AND RADIATOR COULD BE SEEN INSIDE.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO A MIDWAY AIRLINES TICKET COUNTER EMPLOYEE WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE PHOENIX P.D. (REPORT ATTACHED).  THE TWO CONTRACT EMPLOYEES HANDLING THE BOX WERE ADMINISTERED FIRST AID BUT REFUSED ANY FURTHER MEDICAL TREATMENT.  STATEMENTS OF ALL INVOLVED AND A SYNOPSIS REPORT WERE FORWARDED TO: SPECIAL AGENT NOVA HAUFLE CIVIL AVIATION SECURITY FIELD OFFICE 2800 SKY HARBOR BLVD, ROOM 128 PHOENIX, ARIZONA  85034 TEL: (602) 379-6021

column168: RAILROAD EMPLOYEES REPORTED LEAKAGE FROM ACFX 76397 IN TOPEKA, KS RAILYARD, WITH SMOKE OBSERVED COMING FROM AREA OF LEAKAGE.  CAR PREVIOUSLY UNLOADED BY CONSIGNEE AND FILLED WITH WATER PRIOR TO RETURN ROUTE, ( AS IS NORMAL PROCEDURE).  INSPECTION BY CONSIGNEE DETERMINED LEAK WAS AT THE BASE OF THE WATER INLET VALVE NIPPLE (DEFECTIVE THREADS).  WHEN CAR WAS MOVED, WATER CONTAINING RESIDUE WAS LEAKING AND RUNNING DOWN SIDE OF THE RAILCAR WITH RESIDUE IGNITING UPON CONTACT WITH AIR.  AREA OF LEAK WAS PACKED WITH SILICON BY CONSIGNEE TO PREVENT FURTHER RELEASE.  CAR WAS THEN MOVED BY SWITCH CREW AND MOVEMENT MONITORED BY DISTRICT SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (DSA/HM) KEN DECHANT.  INSPECTION OF VALVE PRIOER TO MOVE AND AFTER WARM, DISCLOSED NO ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  CAR TO BE RETURNED TO CONSIGNEE FOR REPLACEMENT OF VALVE.
